window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"Which of the following organisms is not classified as an animal?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amoeba","B":"Paramecium","C":"Euglena","D":"Obelia"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Euglena is not classified as an animal. It is a unicellular organism that is often classified as a protist. Protists are a diverse group of eukaryotic microorganisms, which are not animals, plants or fungi. They are primarily unicellular, but there are some multicellular species. Euglena has characteristics of both plants and animals. Like plants, it can perform photosynthesis, but like animals, it can also take in food from its environment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"An organism that operates at the cellular level of organization carries out its physiological activities by using its","images":[],"options":{"A":"cell membrane","B":"organelles","C":"nucleus","D":"cell wall"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An organism that operates at the cellular level of organization carries out its physiological activities by using its organelles. Organelles are specialized structures within the cell that work together to help the cell function. They include structures such as the nucleus (which controls the cell's activities), the mitochondria (which produce energy), and the ribosomes (which make proteins). The cell membrane and cell wall are involved in protecting the cell and regulating the movement of substances in and out of the cell, but they do not carry out the cell's physiological activities.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"The organelle which eliminates water from the body of a protozoan is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"plasma membrane","B":"contractile vacuole","C":"nucleus","D":"cell wall"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The removal of water from the body of a protozoan is part of the process of osmoregulation. Contractile vacuole performs the function of osmoregulation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Which of the following cell types has the least number of mitochondria?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Cardiac cells of the heart","B":"Cells of the cornified layer","C":"Muscle cells of the bladder","D":"Muscle cells of the diaphragm"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The cells of the cornified layer, also known as the stratum corneum in the skin, have the least number of mitochondria. This is because these cells are dead and filled with keratin, a protein that provides a barrier against environmental damage. They do not require energy for metabolic processes, unlike other cells such as cardiac cells or muscle cells, which have a high energy demand and therefore a high number of mitochondria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"A typical plant cell is mainly distinguished from an animal cell by the possession of","images":[],"options":{"A":"chloroplast and nucleus","B":"cell wall and cytoplasm","C":"chloroplast and cell wall","D":"cell wall and mitochondrion"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A typical plant cell is mainly distinguished from an animal cell by the possession of chloroplast and cell wall. Chloroplasts are the site of photosynthesis in plant cells, a process that is not present in animal cells. The cell wall, made of cellulose, provides structural support to the plant cell, another feature not found in animal cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"Which of the following characteristics do fungi share in common with animals?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Presence of digestive tract","B":"Movement from one place to another","C":"Storage of carbohydrate as glycogen","D":"Movement of centrioles during cell division"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fungi and animals both store carbohydrates as glycogen. This is a form of energy storage used by animals and fungi that is efficient for rapid energy release. Unlike plants which store energy as starch, animals and fungi convert glucose into glycogen for storage.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"Which of the following processes involves diffusion?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Opening and closing of stomatal pores","B":"Turgidity of herbaceous plants","C":"Absorption of water through the root hairs","D":"Absorption of digested food into the villi"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Diffusion is the movement of particles from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. Here's how it relates to the options given:    -Opening and closing of stomatal pores: This is controlled by the turgidity of guard cells, primarily influenced by osmosis and the active transport of ions, not diffusion.    -Turgidity of herbaceous plants: This involves osmosis, which is the movement of water across a semi-permeable membrane, not diffusion.    -Absorption of water through the root hairs: This primarily occurs through osmosis, where water moves from the soil (higher water potential) to the root cells (lower water potential).    -Absorption of digested food into the villi: This involves diffusion. Nutrients like glucose and amino acids, once broken down, move from the intestinal lumen (where they are in higher concentration) into the blood capillaries within the villi (where they are in lower concentration).    Thus, the process of absorbing digested food into the villi is an example of diffusion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"The mechanism of opening and closing of stomata in plants is based on","images":[],"options":{"A":"turgidity and diffusion","B":"turgidity and flaccidity","C":"osmosis and diffusion","D":"diffusion and flaccidity"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The opening and closing of the stomata is controlled by turgidity and flaccidity respectively. When the guard cells are turgid, the guard cells which control the opening and closing of stomata opens and when the guard cells are flaccid, the stomata closes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"In cellular respiration energy is made available to organism by","images":[],"options":{"A":"removal of a phosphate group from ADP","B":"breaking off a phosphate group from ATP","C":"adding a phosphate group to glucose","D":"breaking off a hydrogen ion from NADPH"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When ATP is converted to adenosine diphosphate (ADP), it loses a phosphate (P1). Energy us released when the bond connecting the phosphate is broken.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Excretion in paramecium sp, is by diffusion because","images":[],"options":{"A":"its habitat is water and moist places","B":"it has simple, small and few internal organs","C":"it has a large surface area to volume ratio","D":"it has a large efficient meganucleus"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Excretion in Paramecium sp., is by diffusion because it has a large surface area to volume ratio. Diffusion is the movement of molecules from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. In the case of Paramecium, which is a unicellular organism, the large surface area to volume ratio allows for efficient diffusion of waste materials out of the cell.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The axial skeleton is composed of the","images":[],"options":{"A":"skull and vertebral column","B":"limbs and girdles","C":"atlas and axis","D":"radius and ulna"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The axial skeleton is part of the skeleton that consists of the bones of the head and trunk of a vertebrate. It is composed of the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs, and the sternum. Therefore, the correct answer is 'skull and vertebral column'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The inorganic components of bone consist of","images":[],"options":{"A":"magnesium, sodium and calcium","B":"magnesium, phosphorus and calcium","C":"sodium, phosphorus and calcium","D":"potassium, magnesium and calcium"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The inorganic components of bone consist of hydroxyapatite, a crystalline structure composed of calcium, phosphate, and hydroxide ions. Other minerals present in bone include magnesium and sodium. Therefore, the correct answer is 'magnesium, phosphorus and calcium'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"A pulse is best described as","images":[],"options":{"A":"contraction of arteries to let out blood","B":"contraction of veins to allow blood into them","C":"dilation of arteries to accomodate blood rushing through","D":"pumping action of the heart to move blood round the body"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When the heart beats, it pumps blood into the arteries, causing them to expand (dilate) to accommodate the surge of blood. This expansion and subsequent recoil can be felt as a pulse at various points on the body where the arteries are close to the skin.  why the other options are incorrect:  -Contraction of arteries to let out blood: Arteries do not contract to let out blood. The heart's pumping action forces blood into the arteries, causing them to expand. Arteries can contract to help regulate blood pressure, but this is not what creates the pulse.    -Contraction of veins to allow blood into them. Veins do not significantly contract to allow blood into them. Blood flow through veins is aided by the contraction of surrounding muscles and valves that prevent backflow, not by the veins themselves contracting in a way that would generate a pulse.    -Pumping action of the heart to move blood round the body**: While the heart's pumping action is crucial for moving blood around the body and creating the pulse, the pulse itself is specifically the result of the dilation of arteries in response to the surge of blood. This option is too broad and does not describe the pulse as the arterial dilation does.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"The following characteristics are associated with the mammalian lungs except","images":[],"options":{"A":"large surface area","B":"expandable lungs","C":"moist surface","D":"highly vascularized"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The mammalian lungs are not expandable. They are elastic, meaning they can stretch and then return to their original shape, but they do not expand in the sense of growing larger. The other options are correct: the lungs do have a large surface area, a moist surface for gas exchange, and are highly vascularized, meaning they have a large number of blood vessels.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"The excretory system in mammals consists of the following parts except","images":[],"options":{"A":"two kidney","B":"two ureters","C":"two bladders","D":"one urethra"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The excretory system in mammals consists of two kidneys, two ureters, and one urethra. However, mammals do not have two bladders. They only have one bladder. Therefore, the option 'two bladders' is incorrect.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"The organ that receives reduced flow of blood during vigorous exercise is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"brain","B":"heart","C":"lung","D":"limb"},"answer":"A","explanation":"During vigorous exercise, the body prioritizes sending blood to the muscles that are working hard, such as the limbs. As a result, organs like the brain receive a reduced flow of blood. The heart and lungs, on the other hand, receive increased blood flow because they are working harder to supply oxygen and remove carbon dioxide from the body.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"The ear pinna is strengthened by","images":[],"options":{"A":"blood pressure","B":"cartilage","C":"bone","D":"turgor pressure"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The pinna or auricle is the exposed funnel-shaped part of the ear that directs sound waves into the ear. It is a flap made of cartilageneous tissue, the  cartilaginous  tissue maintains the shape of the pinna and offers some flexibility.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The relationship between the retina and the brain is similar to that between the","images":[],"options":{"A":"cochlea and the auditory nerve","B":"cochlea and the brain","C":"cochlea and the semi-circular canals","D":"eardrum and the brain"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The relationship between the retina and the brain is similar to that between the cochlea and the brain in that the stereo cilia in the cochlea respond to vibrations of the fluid in the cochlea and send electric impulses to the brain via the cochlea nerve.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"Which of the following statements about the development of the foetus is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The circulatory system of the foetus is directly connected to the maternal blood vessels","B":"The foetus depends on the mother's blood for its food and oxygen","C":"The foetus is surrounded by a water sac","D":"Food and oxygen are carried across the placenta to the embryo's blood"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The circulatory system of the foetus is not directly connected to the maternal blood vessels. Instead, the mother's and foetus's blood supplies are separated by the placenta, which allows for the exchange of nutrients and waste products without the two blood supplies mixing. This is a crucial aspect of foetal development as it protects the foetus from potential infections and harmful substances that may be present in the mother's blood.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Use the diagram beside to answer this question      The parts that supply food and water to the developing embryo are labelled","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I and II","B":"III and V","C":"V and VI","D":"II and III"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The parts labelled V and VI supply food and water to the developing embryo. The part labelled V is the albumen which provides food (mainly protein and salts) and water for embryo. The part labelled VI is the yolk which provides food (mainly fats and proteins) for embryo.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"Use the diagram beside to answer this question    The part labelled III is the","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"albumen","B":"chalaza","C":"yolk","D":"air space"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The part labelled III is the chalaza. The chalaza is a strands of albumen that supports the yolk.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"Which of the following statements is true about transpiration? It is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"loss of water in the form of vapour from the surface of the leaf","B":"loss of water in the form of vapour from the surface of the root","C":"absorption of water in the form of vapour from the body of the plant","D":"movement of water through the body of the plant"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Transpiration is the process by which water is lost from a plant in the form of water vapour. This primarily occurs at the leaves of the plant, specifically through tiny openings called stomata. The water vapour is created when water from the plant's cells evaporates into the air spaces within the leaf, and then exits the leaf through the stomata. Therefore, the statement 'loss of water in the form of vapour from the surface of the leaf' is true about transpiration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"Transportation of water in the xylem tissue involves the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"root pressure","B":"capillary action","C":"transpiration pull","D":"translocation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Root pressure, capillary action and transpiration pull are the factors involved in the movement of water in the xylem. Xylem is a tissue that conducts water in plants.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The following are the major reasons why the butterfly lays eggs under the surface of a leaf except to","images":[],"options":{"A":"shade the eggs from the direct rays of the sun","B":"protect the eggs from predators","C":"protect the eggs from being washed away by rain drops","D":"camouflage the eggs"},"answer":"D","explanation":"All the options given are reasons why a butterfly lays its eggs under the surface of a leaf except for camouflage. While it's true that the underside of a leaf can provide some degree of camouflage, this is not the primary reason why butterflies choose to lay their eggs there. The main reasons are to protect the eggs from predators, shield them from the direct rays of the sun, and prevent them from being washed away by rain.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"In which of the following organic compounds is the hydrogen-oxygen ratio equal to 2:1?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Protein","B":"Carbohydrates","C":"Lipids","D":"Vitamins"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The hydrogen-oxygen ratio in carbohydrates is 2:1. This is because carbohydrates are organic compounds composed of carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen, and the hydrogen and oxygen are usually in the ratio of 2:1, similar to water. This is not the case for proteins, lipids, or vitamins.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"A man suffering from obesity must avoid meals containing","images":[],"options":{"A":"margarine and butter","B":"rice and beans","C":"carrots and oranges","D":"beef and fish"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Obesity is a condition that arises mainly due to excess fat in the body. Margarine and better are fat-containing food. A person suffering from obesity should avoid meals containing fat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"In testing for starch in a leaf, the leaf is first boiled in water for about a minute so that the","images":[],"options":{"A":"cells walls are hardened","B":"cells are killed","C":"chrolophyl is dissolved out","D":"iodine will penetrate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The leaf is first boiled in order to kill the cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following food substances is incorrectly linked to its enzyme?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Protein - trypsin","B":"Fat - lipase","C":"Sucrose - pepsin","D":"Starch- amylase"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The enzyme pepsin does not break down sucrose. Pepsin is a protease enzyme that breaks down proteins into smaller peptides. It is produced in the stomach and is one of the main digestive enzymes in the digestive systems of humans and many other animals. On the other hand, sucrose is a type of sugar that is broken down by the enzyme sucrase, not pepsin.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following pH values is the best for the action of the enzymes - renin and pepsin in the stomach?","images":[],"options":{"A":"pH 2","B":"pH 7","C":"pH 8","D":"pH 9"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Renin and pepsin are enzymes found in the stomach that help in the digestion of proteins. These enzymes work best in an acidic environment, which is provided by the hydrochloric acid in the stomach. The pH of the stomach is typically around 2, which is highly acidic. Therefore, the best pH for the action of renin and pepsin is pH 2.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"The bacterium in a mutualistic association with legumes converts","images":[],"options":{"A":"nitrates to ammonia","B":"ammonium compounds to nitrites","C":"nitrogen gas to ammonia","D":"nitrites to nitrates"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Rhizobium bacteria are found in the root nodules of leguminous plants. The bacteria obtain carbohydrates from the plants and at the same time provide the plants with ammonium compounds which they obtain through nitrogen fixation. Bacteria like Rhizobium that lives in the root nodules of leguminous plants are able to fix nitrogen found in the soil particles to ammonium compounds.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : FEEDING HABITS","question":"A herbivore cannot feed on a piece of meat because it has no","images":[],"options":{"A":"incisors to cut the meat","B":"canines to tear up the meat","C":"premolars to grind the meat","D":"molar to mash the meat"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Herbivores lack canines, hence, they cannot feed on a piece of meat. Instead of the canines, between the incisors and the premolars there is a gap, the diastema.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"In a particular habitat the role of an organism is referred to as its","images":[],"options":{"A":"level","B":"biomass","C":"niche","D":"space"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In ecology, the term 'niche' refers to the role or function of an organism within its ecosystem. This includes its interactions with other organisms, its diet, its behavior, and the physical conditions necessary for its survival. Therefore, in a particular habitat, the role of an organism is referred to as its niche.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The distribution of organisms in a fresh water habitat like a stream or pond is determined by the following factors except","images":[],"options":{"A":"light penetration","B":"pH of the soil","C":"rainfall","D":"temperature"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The pH of the soil does not affect the distribution of organisms in a fresh water habitat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The speed of wind is measured using the","images":[],"options":{"A":"wind vane","B":"anemometer","C":"photometer","D":"barometer"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The speed of wind is measured using an anemometer. An anemometer is a device used for measuring the speed of wind, and is also a common weather station instrument. The term is derived from the Greek word anemos, which means wind, and is used to describe any wind speed instrument used in meteorology. The other options, wind vane, photometer, and barometer, are used for measuring wind direction, light intensity, and atmospheric pressure respectively.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"Which of the following is a biotic component of an ecosystem?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Soil","B":"Rainfall","C":"Light","D":"Fungi"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A biotic component of an ecosystem refers to the living organisms that inhabit the ecosystem. This includes animals, plants, fungi, and bacteria. In the given options, 'Fungi' is the only biotic component. Soil, Rainfall, and Light are all abiotic components, which refer to the non-living physical and chemical elements in an ecosystem.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"A moss plant can withstand drought by means of its","images":[],"options":{"A":"spores","B":"rhizoids","C":"antheridia","D":"archegonia"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Moss plants are non-vascular plants that can withstand drought by means of their spores. Spores are a means of reproduction for moss, but they also allow the moss to survive in harsh conditions. When conditions are too dry for the moss to survive, it can release its spores, which are resistant to drought. The spores can then germinate when conditions become more favorable. Rhizoids, antheridia, and archegonia are also parts of a moss plant, but they do not help the plant withstand drought.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following factors is the main problem facing xerophytic plants?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Competition for sunlight","B":"Conservation of excess water","C":"Inadequate roots for water absorption","D":"Lack of adequate water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Xerophytic plants are plants that have adapted to survive in an environment with little liquid water, such as an arid desert or an ice- or snow-covered region in the Alps or the Arctic. The main problem facing xerophytic plants is the lack of adequate water. This is because water is essential for photosynthesis, a process in which plants convert light energy, usually from the Sun, into chemical energy that can be later released to fuel the organisms' activities.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : POLLUTION OF THE ATMOSPHERE","question":"The following are greenhouse gases except","images":[],"options":{"A":"carbon dioxide","B":"chlorofluorocarbon","C":"methane","D":"oxygen"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Greenhouse gases are gases in Earth's atmosphere that trap heat. They let sunlight pass through the atmosphere, but they prevent the heat that the sunlight brings from leaving the atmosphere. The main greenhouse gases are: water vapor, carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and chlorofluorocarbons. Oxygen is not a greenhouse gas because it does not trap heat in the Earth's atmosphere.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT","question":"Rural-urban migration in developing countries can be prevented by","images":[],"options":{"A":"increasing the number of years in school","B":"putting up more factories in urban areas","C":"having boarding schools in rural areas","D":"even distribution of facilities in both regions"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Rural-urban migration in developing countries can be prevented by even distribution of facilities in both regions. This is because one of the main reasons for rural-urban migration is the search for better facilities and opportunities which are often concentrated in urban areas. If facilities such as schools, hospitals, and job opportunities are evenly distributed in both rural and urban areas, people would have less incentive to migrate.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Muscles are attached to bones by means of","images":[],"options":{"A":"tendons","B":"ligaments","C":"cartilage","D":"nerves"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Muscles are attached to bones by means of tendons. Tendons are tough bands of fibrous connective tissue that usually connect muscle to bone and are capable of withstanding tension. Ligaments, on the other hand, connect bone to bone, cartilage is a flexible connective tissue found in many areas in the bodies of humans and other animals, and nerves are the core components of the body's nervous system.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : FACTORS THAT AFFECT POPULATION","question":"In a population, food shortage may lead to","images":[],"options":{"A":"an increased survival rate","B":"high reproduction rate","C":"intra-specific competition","D":"low rate of migration"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a population, food shortage may lead to intra-specific competition. Intra-specific competition refers to the competition between members of the same species for limited resources, such as food. When there is a food shortage, individuals within the same species will compete for the limited food resources, leading to intra-specific competition.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"The following effects are associated with deforestation except","images":[],"options":{"A":"gully erosion","B":"extinction of plant species","C":"migration of wild life","D":"increase in rainfall"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The damaging effects of soil erosion include:  1. Soil erosion  2. Flooding   3. Desertification: which also leads to   a. A loss of habitat  b. an extinction of many species of organisms (plants & animals)  c. climatic changes","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"The main reason for the conservation of wildlife is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"create national parks for recreation","B":"maintain ecological balance in communities","C":"prevent hunters from being cruel to animals","D":"save some species from extinction"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The main reason for conservation is to save some species from extinction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following is an example of variation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Blood","B":"Tongue rolling","C":"Reproduction","D":"Growth"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Variation refers to the differences in physical traits among individuals from the same species. Tongue rolling is an example of variation because not everyone can roll their tongue into a tube shape. This is a genetic trait, and it varies from person to person. The other options like Blood, Reproduction, and Growth are not examples of variation as they are common biological processes or components in all individuals of a species.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"The parameters of size, height, weight and colour in a population of living things are examples of","images":[],"options":{"A":"environmental variations","B":"non-heritable variations","C":"continuous variations","D":"discontinuous variations"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Continuous variations are those that have a complete range of measurements from one extreme to another. They are usually quantitative and can be measured. Examples include height, weight, and skin color in a population. These traits are controlled by two or more genes, which makes them polygenic. The genes interact with each other and the environment to bring about a wide range of phenotypes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Fingerprints are useful in crime detection because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the police have sophisticated fingerprint machines","B":"thieves may leave their prints at the scene of a crime","C":"no two people have the same fingerprint","D":"fingerprints are easy to make"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fingerprints are unique to each individual, even identical twins do not have exactly the same fingerprints. This uniqueness makes fingerprints a very reliable method of identification. This is why they are used in crime detection, as they can help to identify the person who was at the scene of a crime.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"A person with blood group O can be given blood from persons who have blood belonging to","images":[],"options":{"A":"group O only","B":"group A only","C":"groups A and O","D":"group A, B and O"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A person with blood group O is considered a universal donor, but they can only receive blood from individuals of the same blood group, which is O. This is because blood group O does not have any antigens that would cause an immune response if transfused into another person. However, if a person with blood group O receives blood from any other group (A, B, or AB), their immune system would recognize the antigens on the red blood cells as foreign and mount an immune response, leading to a transfusion reaction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"A man heterozygous for albino gene marries a woman who is also heterozygous for the gene. Both have normal skin colour. The probability that they will have an albino child is","images":[],"options":{"A":"1/3","B":"1/4","C":"4/4","D":"2/4"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Albinism is a recessive trait, meaning that an individual must inherit two copies of the albino gene (one from each parent) to express the trait. If both parents are heterozygous for the albino gene (meaning they each carry one copy of the albino gene and one copy of the normal gene), then there is a 1 in 4 chance that any given child will inherit two copies of the albino gene and therefore be albino. This is determined using a Punnett square, a diagram that is used to predict the outcome of a particular cross or breeding experiment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following statements about heredity is not true? In hereditary the traits are","images":[],"options":{"A":"carried by genes","B":"contained in the ovum and sperm","C":"always transmitted by one parent","D":"transmitted from parents to offspring"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Heredity is the process by which traits are passed from parents to offspring. These traits are carried by genes, which are contained in the ovum and sperm. However, it is not true that traits are always transmitted by one parent. In most cases, traits are inherited from both parents, which is why offspring often have characteristics of both parents. Therefore, the statement 'always transmitted by one parent' is not true.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"An example of a saprophytic relationship is a/an","images":[],"options":{"A":"vulture feeding on decaying meat","B":"mushroom growing on decaying vegetation","C":"boy eating stale bread","D":"earthworm feeding on decaying vegetation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a saprophyte relationship, only one living organism is involved. The living organism is usually the decomposer (fungus or bacterium) and the non-living component is the dead-decaying matter.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>51","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"In artificial selection, individuals without desirable traits may be prevented from mating by","images":[],"options":{"A":"outbreeding","B":"sterilization","C":"inbreeding","D":"genetic engineering"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Artificial selection is a process used by humans to develop new organisms with desirable characteristics. Breeders select two parents that have beneficial phenotypic traits to reproduce, yielding offspring with those desired traits. Individuals without desirable traits may be prevented from mating by sterilization. Sterilization is a process that eliminates or kills all forms of life, including transmissible agents (such as fungi, bacteria, viruses, spore forms, etc.) present on a surface, contained in a fluid, in medication, or in a compound.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>52","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"In a family of eight (8) all the children are girls. Which of the following reasons correctly explains this?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The woman cannot produce male children","B":"The man has a low sperm count","C":"The Y component of the man's sex chromosome was always involved","D":"The X component of the man's sex chromosomes was always involved"},"answer":"D","explanation":"- This is because the X component of the man's sex chromosome was always involved.  - In men, we have XY genotype and in female, we have XX genotype.  During sex determination, when the X component of the female sex chromosome is released and the X component of the male sex chromosome is released, the baby will be female also, when the X component of the female sex chromosome is released, and the Y component of the male sex chromosome is released, the baby will be male.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>53","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Which of the following statements is correct about the structure of a chromosome? A chromosome consists of","images":[],"options":{"A":"two chromatids joined at the centromere","B":"two chromatids joined at the spindle","C":"two chromatin threads joined at the centrioles","D":"threas-like structures not joined together"},"answer":"A","explanation":"During cell division, the chromosomes are duplicated and become visible under the microscope as long and thin threads that are between 0.25\u03bcm and 50\u03bcm in length. Each duplicated chromosome is made up of two sister chromatids attached by a centromere.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>54","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"Mr. Andrew, his wife and child belong to blood group A, B and O respectively. The genotypes of both parents are","images":[],"options":{"A":"IAIO and IBIB","B":"IAIA and IBIB","C":"IAIB and IAIO","D":"IAIO and IBIO"},"answer":"D","explanation":"|A|B |A|o |B|o |O|o - the child/offspring","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>55","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"What would be the phenotypic ratio of the offspring of a cross between a heterozygous dominant parent and a double recessive parent?","images":[],"options":{"A":"1 : 2 : 1","B":"1 : 1","C":"3 : 1","D":"2 : 1"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Let the heterozygous dominant parent be Rr the double recessive parent rr  Parent Rr &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp X &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp rr","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>56","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : LINKAGE, SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"The percentage probability that a normal male married to a carrier woman would have a haemophilic male child is","images":[],"options":{"A":"35%","B":"50%","C":"75%","D":"100%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Let the normal man be XY  the carries woman be XcXc    Hemophilic male is 2  24\u00d7100=50%","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>57","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The importance of courtship in animals includes the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"ensuring that the female choose the right male species","B":"arousing both male and female partners","C":"protection of territory","D":"to coincide with the ovulation period and ensure fertilization"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Courtship in animals serves several purposes such as ensuring that the female chooses the right male species, arousing both male and female partners, and to coincide with the ovulation period to ensure fertilization. However, courtship does not directly involve the protection of territory. While some animals may use courtship displays to assert dominance or territorial control, the act of courtship itself is not a mechanism for territory protection.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>58","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"In evolution, analogous structures are significant because they show","images":[],"options":{"A":"physiological diversity","B":"functional diversity","C":"genetic diversity","D":"structural diversity"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Analogous structures in evolution are significant because they show functional diversity. Analogous structures are those that perform similar functions but are not necessarily structurally similar or have a common ancestor. They are a result of convergent evolution where different species have independently evolved similar solutions to similar environmental challenges. This shows functional diversity as different species have developed similar functions to adapt to their environment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>59","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following statements reflects the mechanism of natural selection?","images":[],"options":{"A":"There are variations within every species","B":"Individuals of every species are generally identical","C":"No organism in a species dies before sexual maturity","D":"Organism with selective advantages are less likely to survive"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The statement that reflects the mechanism of natural selection is 'There are variations within every species'. Natural selection is a process where organisms with variations that make them better adapted to their environment tend to survive and reproduce more than those without these variations. This leads to the changes in the species over time. The other options do not accurately reflect the mechanism of natural selection.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2010>60","subject":"Biology","year":"2010","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Which of the following animals exhibits territoriality?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Rabbit","B":"Earthworm","C":"Lizard","D":"Toad"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Territoriality is a type of behavior in which an animal defends a bounded physical space against intrusion by other individuals, usually of its own species. Lizards are known to exhibit this behavior, marking and defending their territories from other males and sometimes females, too.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];